CHROME LIFECYCLE FIX — VALIDATED LIVE IN PRACTICE + ESM REGRESSION CAUGHT (2026-05-29, gm-plugkit 2.0.1505). The chrome-lifecycle fix (76380ff3/a51623cd) shipped to npm 2.0.1504 but BRICKED the watcher: I added a top-level require('./browser-idle.js') in the wrapper, which is an ESM file (import fs from 'fs' at line 1, node reparses as ESM, no package.json type) -> ReferenceError: require is not defined in ES module scope at boot -> dead watcher, and the self-stale probe kept respawning the SAME broken 2.0.1504 in a crash loop. FIX (c0620102 -> npm 2.0.1505): inlined selectIdleBrowserSessions back into the wrapper (no cross-file require); kept gm-plugkit/browser-idle.js + browser-idle.test.js for unit-test only. LESSON: NEVER add `require(...)` to plugkit-wasm-wrapper.js — it is loaded as ESM; use inline functions or `import`. A separate-module + require refactor that passes `node file.test.js` standalone can still brick the ESM-loaded wrapper. VALIDATED LIVE on 2.0.1505 (the validate-prior-commit mandate working exactly as intended): (1) lastUse stamp — browser session new -> ports.json entry carries lastUse:<ms> (ABSENT on old wrapper) = cross-scope lastBrowserActivityMs bug fixed, stampBrowserLastUse runs. (2) per-session idle close — backdated ports[sid].lastUse to 11min-ago (>10min default), one 60s sweep -> ports.json {} (entry removed) + chrome pid DEAD (gracefulCloseBrowser ran). (3) isolation — gm ports.json is per-cwd single-entry; other cwds untouched (structural). (4) seamless reopen — startManagedBrowser branch spawns fresh on next verb (same code that spawned the test session). NOTICES: (a) browser.idle-closed logEvent did NOT surface in a .watcher.log grep though the close demonstrably ran — minor observability gap (the event may write a different channel or the log rotated). (b) The watcher died repeatedly under my rapid kill/reboot deploy churn this session — each recovery was a clean bun x gm-plugkit@latest spool reboot; the deploy-kill + self-stale-respawn + manual-reboot interplay is fragile under back-to-back deploys but each individual reboot recovers. DEPLOY LESSON: to deploy a wrapper fix that is ALREADY published, a clean `bun x gm-plugkit@latest --kill-stale-watchers; bun x gm-plugkit@latest spool` pulls the latest; if the latest npm is itself broken, you must republish (commit+push) FIRST because bun x re-downloads the broken version over any local patch and the self-stale loop re-pulls it.